# """

2026 JAPANESE GP RACE PREDICTION MODEL — SUZUKA
Round 3 | March 29, 2026
============================================================

# HOW THIS MODEL WORKS — A FULL WALKTHROUGH

STEP 1 — DATA COLLECTION
We manually gather real-world data for each driver:

- Qualifying lap times from Q3 (pole gap)
- Grid positions
- Race pace from practice long runs
- Track-specific factors (tyre wear, ERS efficiency)
- Team constructor points (proxy for car performance)

STEP 2 — FEATURE ENGINEERING
Raw data is transformed into numeric "features" the
ML model can learn from. E.g. team names → point scores.

STEP 3 — GRADIENT BOOSTING REGRESSOR
We use sklearn's GradientBoostingRegressor. This is an
ensemble model that builds many small decision trees
sequentially — each tree corrects the errors of the
previous one. It's excellent for small tabular datasets.

Key hyperparameters:
n_estimators=100 → number of trees to build
learning_rate=0.08 → how much each tree contributes
max_depth=4 → complexity of each tree
random_state=39 → ensures reproducible results

STEP 4 — LEAVE-ONE-OUT CROSS VALIDATION (LOO)
Because we have a small dataset (~6–8 drivers), standard
train/test splits are unreliable. LOO works like this: - For each driver, train the model on ALL other drivers - Predict that one driver's race time - Measure the error (Mean Absolute Error = MAE) - Average the errors across all drivers
This gives a realistic estimate of model accuracy.

STEP 5 — FINAL PREDICTION
The model is retrained on ALL data, then used to predict
race times. Drivers are ranked by predicted race time.

# SUZUKA-SPECIFIC ADAPTATIONS vs CHINA

China (Shanghai) had: - 1.2km main straight (ERS very important) - Low tyre degradation track - Pole lap ~91.8s

Suzuka is fundamentally different: - 5.807km circuit, 53 laps - HIGH-SPEED corner sequences (130R, S-curves, Degner) - Medium-high tyre degradation (rear-limited) - Pole lap ~88.x seconds (shorter lap time) - ERS energy harvest still relevant but aero balance
and mechanical grip matter MORE than straight-line speed - "Suzuka_Confidence" replaces EnergyHarvest as the
key differentiator — some drivers/cars are simply
more at home on this track's demands.

DATA SOURCES:

- Qualifying: RacingNews365, PlanetF1, GPFans (March 28 2026)
- Standings: Total-Motorsport, Crash.net (post China GP)
- Practice pace: F1.com FP1/FP2 reports
  """

import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from sklearn.ensemble import GradientBoostingRegressor
from sklearn.model_selection import LeaveOneOut
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error

# ============================================================

# SECTION 1: CONTEXT — JAPAN GP (ROUND 3, SUZUKA)

# ============================================================

# Weather: Suzuka in late March — cool, partly cloudy, dry

# Rain probability is low based on forecasts

weather_data = {
"RainProbability": 0.10, # 10% chance — slightly higher than China
"Temperature": 16.0 # degrees Celsius, cooler than Shanghai
}

# Constructor points after Round 2 (China GP).

# These are the REAL standings as of March 15, 2026.

# Higher points = stronger package overall = faster car.

# This feeds into the model as a team performance proxy.

constructor_pts = {
"Mercedes": 98, # Dominant — back-to-back 1-2s
"Ferrari": 67, # Solid 2nd force
"McLaren": 18, # Struggling with reliability (DNS in China)
"Haas": 17, # Surprise package — Bearman shining
"Red Bull": 12, # Worrying slump
"Racing Bulls": 12, # Tied with Red Bull
"Alpine": 10, # Gasly picking up points
"Audi": 2, # Bortoleto into Q3 today — improving
}

# ============================================================

# SECTION 2: DRIVER DATA — SUZUKA QUALIFYING (MARCH 28, 2026)

# ============================================================

#

# FIELD EXPLANATIONS:

#

# Driver — Full name (string, for display only)

# Team — Constructor (mapped to points above)

#

# UltimateLap_S — Best qualifying lap in seconds.

# Antonelli P1: 1:28.877 = 88.877s

# All times converted from m:ss.xxx

#

# JapanGapFromPole_S — Gap to Antonelli's pole time in seconds.

# Pole driver = 0.000. Others are +ve gaps.

# Extracted from qualifying reports.

#

# JapanGrid — Starting position for Sunday's race.

# Based on qualifying order.

#

# ChinaGrid — Their grid position in Round 2 (China).

# Gives context on recent form.

#

# RacePace_CleanAir — Estimated race lap time in clean air (seconds).

# Derived from FP2 long-run data and historical

# Suzuka pace. This is a critical feature —

# qualifying pace ≠ race pace.

#

# TyreDeg — Tyre degradation index (1–10 scale).

# 10 = very high wear. Suzuka is harder on tyres

# than China due to high-speed loaded corners.

# Low deg = driver/car can push longer stints.

#

# Suzuka_Confidence — NEW feature replacing EnergyHarvest.

# Scale 1–10. Reflects how much a driver/car

# excels at Suzuka's specific demands:

# - High-speed corner commitment (130R, Spoon)

# - Mechanical grip in the S-curves

# - Historical Suzuka performance

# 10 = highly confident/suited to this circuit.

#

# ActualRaceTime — This is the TARGET VARIABLE (what we predict).

# Since the race hasn't happened yet, we estimate

# this from a realistic lap-count average.

# Formula: RacePace_CleanAir _ 53 laps _ ~1.012

# (the 1.2% factor accounts for traffic, pit loss,

# slower laps at start/end).

# NOTE: In a post-race model, you'd use the REAL

# race time. Here it's our best pre-race estimate,

# which is what the model then refines.

#

japan_data = [
# --- P1: ANTONELLI — Back-to-back poles. Mercedes is dominant. ---
{
"Driver": "Kimi Antonelli",
"Team": "Mercedes",
"UltimateLap_S": 88.877, # Pole: 1:28.877
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 0.000, # Reference point
"JapanGrid": 1,
"ChinaGrid": 1, # Also pole in China
"RacePace_CleanAir": 92.4, # Strong long-run pace
"TyreDeg": 3.8, # Mercedes manages tyres well
"Suzuka_Confidence": 9.5, # Young but fearless at high speed
"ActualRaceTime": 97.21, # ~92.4 * 53 / 53 equivalent
},
# --- P2: RUSSELL — Front row again. Complained about pace gap. ---
{
"Driver": "George Russell",
"Team": "Mercedes",
"UltimateLap_S": 89.147, # ~0.27s off pole
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 0.270,
"JapanGrid": 2,
"ChinaGrid": 2,
"RacePace_CleanAir": 92.6,
"TyreDeg": 3.9,
"Suzuka_Confidence": 9.2, # Excellent Suzuka record
"ActualRaceTime": 97.43,
},
# --- P3: PIASTRI — Led McLaren charge, strong in high-speed ---
{
"Driver": "Oscar Piastri",
"Team": "McLaren",
"UltimateLap_S": 89.227, # ~0.35s off pole
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 0.350,
"JapanGrid": 3,
"ChinaGrid": 5, # DNS in China race (reliability)
"RacePace_CleanAir": 93.1,
"TyreDeg": 4.2, # McLaren harder on tyres
"Suzuka_Confidence": 8.8,
"ActualRaceTime": 97.88,
},
# --- P4: LECLERC — Mistake on final lap, missed P3 ---
{
"Driver": "Charles Leclerc",
"Team": "Ferrari",
"UltimateLap_S": 89.270, # 0.39s off pole
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 0.393,
"JapanGrid": 4,
"ChinaGrid": 4,
"RacePace_CleanAir": 93.0,
"TyreDeg": 4.0,
"Suzuka_Confidence": 9.0, # Ferrari strong at Suzuka historically
"ActualRaceTime": 97.75,
},
# --- P5: NORRIS — Reliability issues in practice but still P5 ---
{
"Driver": "Lando Norris",
"Team": "McLaren",
"UltimateLap_S": 89.380, # 0.50s off pole
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 0.503,
"JapanGrid": 5,
"ChinaGrid": 20, # DNS in China
"RacePace_CleanAir": 93.3,
"TyreDeg": 4.3,
"Suzuka_Confidence": 8.5,
"ActualRaceTime": 98.05,
},
# --- P6: HAMILTON — Ferrari, aims to repeat China podium ---
{
"Driver": "Lewis Hamilton",
"Team": "Ferrari",
"UltimateLap_S": 89.450, # 0.57s off pole
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 0.573,
"JapanGrid": 6,
"ChinaGrid": 3, # Podium in China (P3)
"RacePace_CleanAir": 93.2,
"TyreDeg": 3.7, # Hamilton known for tyre preservation
"Suzuka_Confidence": 9.8, # Multiple wins/poles at Suzuka
"ActualRaceTime": 97.90,
},
# --- P11: VERSTAPPEN — Shock Q2 exit. "Undriveable" car. ---
{
"Driver": "Max Verstappen",
"Team": "Red Bull",
"UltimateLap_S": 89.900, # Q2 time, not Q3
"JapanGapFromPole_S": 1.023,
"JapanGrid": 11,
"ChinaGrid": 8, # Retired in China
"RacePace_CleanAir": 93.8, # Still has race pace when car works
"TyreDeg": 5.1, # Red Bull struggling with deg
"Suzuka_Confidence": 8.0, # Past winner but car is wrong
"ActualRaceTime": 98.95,
},
]

# ============================================================

# SECTION 3: BUILD THE DATAFRAME & ENGINEER FEATURES

# ============================================================

df = pd.DataFrame(japan_data)

# Map team name → constructor points.

# This gives the model a numeric signal for car performance.

# E.g. Mercedes (98) vs Red Bull (12) — large gap reflects reality.

df["TeamScore"] = df["Team"].map(constructor_pts).fillna(0)

# Add weather as constant columns across all rows.

# In a multi-race model, these would vary per race.

# With 0.10 rain prob, the model gives a small penalty to

# drivers who struggle in changeable conditions.

df["RainProbability"] = weather_data["RainProbability"]
df["Temperature"] = weather_data["Temperature"]

# ============================================================

# SECTION 4: DEFINE FEATURES AND TARGET

# ============================================================

#

# FEATURES (X) — what the model learns FROM:

# UltimateLap_S → raw speed over one lap

# JapanGapFromPole_S → relative pace vs pole

# JapanGrid → track position advantage at race start

# ChinaGrid → recent form indicator (momentum)

# TeamScore → car competitiveness (constructor pts)

# RacePace_CleanAir → sustained pace over race distance

# TyreDeg → ability to manage tyres across stints

# Suzuka_Confidence → circuit-specific performance factor

#

# TARGET (y) — what the model predicts:

# ActualRaceTime → estimated race average lap time (seconds)

#

features = [
"UltimateLap_S",
"JapanGapFromPole_S",
"JapanGrid",
"ChinaGrid",
"TeamScore",
"RacePace_CleanAir",
"TyreDeg",
"Suzuka_Confidence",
]

X = df[features]
y = df["ActualRaceTime"]

# ============================================================

# SECTION 5: LEAVE-ONE-OUT CROSS VALIDATION

# ============================================================

#

# Why LOO? With only 7 drivers in the dataset, a standard

# 80/20 train-test split would leave only 1-2 drivers for

# testing — too small to be meaningful.

#

# LOO solves this by:

# 1. Removing ONE driver at a time (the "test" set)

# 2. Training the model on the remaining 6 drivers

# 3. Predicting the removed driver's race time

# 4. Computing MAE for that prediction

# 5. Repeating for every driver

# 6. Averaging all MAEs for the final reported error

#

# Result: we get 7 independent error estimates, one per driver.

# The average MAE tells us: "on average, how many seconds off

# is the model's prediction?"

loo = LeaveOneOut()
errors = []

for train_index, test_index in loo.split(X):
X_train, X_test = X.iloc[train_index], X.iloc[test_index]
y_train, y_test = y.iloc[train_index], y.iloc[test_index]

    # Fresh model instance each fold — avoids data leakage
    model = GradientBoostingRegressor(
        n_estimators=100,     # 100 sequential trees
        learning_rate=0.08,   # shrinks each tree's contribution
        max_depth=4,          # each tree can split 4 levels deep
        random_state=39       # fixed seed for reproducibility
    )
    model.fit(X_train, y_train)
    pred = model.predict(X_test)
    errors.append(mean_absolute_error(y_test, pred))

# ============================================================

# SECTION 6: FINAL MODEL — TRAIN ON ALL DATA, PREDICT

# ============================================================

#

# Now we train on the FULL dataset (all 7 drivers) to get

# the best possible predictions. This uses all available

# information and produces our final race time estimates.

model.fit(X, y)
df["PredictedRaceTime"] = model.predict(X).round(3)

# Sort drivers by predicted race time (ascending = faster = better)

df = df.sort_values("PredictedRaceTime").reset_index(drop=True)
df.index += 1 # Start ranking from 1

# ============================================================

# SECTION 7: OUTPUT — FORMATTED PREDICTION TABLE

# ============================================================

print("\n" + "=" _ 90)
print("🏁 2026 JAPANESE GP RACE PREDICTION — SUZUKA 🏁")
print(" Round 3 | March 29, 2026 | 53 Laps | 5.807 km")
print("=" _ 90)
print(f"{'Pos':<6} {'Driver':<20} {'Grid':<6} {'Tyre Deg':<10} {'Suzuka Conf':<13} {'Race Pace':<12} {'Pred Time'}")
print("-" \* 90)

for idx, row in df.iterrows():
medal = {1: "🥇", 2: "🥈", 3: "🥉"}.get(idx, f"P{idx} ")
print(
f"{medal:<6} "
f"{row['Driver']:<20} "
f"P{int(row['JapanGrid']):<5} "
f"{row['TyreDeg']:>8.1f} "
f"{row['Suzuka_Confidence']:>11}/10 "
f"{row['RacePace_CleanAir']:>10.1f}s "
f"{row['PredictedRaceTime']:>9.3f}s"
)

print("=" _ 90)
print(f"📊 Leave-One-Out Cross-Validation MAE: {np.mean(errors):.4f} seconds")
print(f" (On average, predictions are within {np.mean(errors):.2f}s of actual race time)")
print("=" _ 90)

# ============================================================

# SECTION 8: FEATURE IMPORTANCE — WHAT DRIVES PREDICTIONS?

# ============================================================

#

# Gradient Boosting tracks how much each feature reduces

# prediction error across all trees. Higher = more influential.

importance*df = pd.DataFrame({
"Feature": features,
"Importance": model.feature_importances*
}).sort_values("Importance", ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

print("\n📈 FEATURE IMPORTANCE (what the model relies on most):")
print("-" _ 45)
for \_, row in importance_df.iterrows():
bar = "█" _ int(row["Importance"] _ 50)
print(f" {row['Feature']:<25} {row['Importance']:.4f} {bar}")
print("=" _ 90)

# ============================================================

# SECTION 9: SUZUKA INSIGHT NOTES

# ============================================================

print("""
🔍 SUZUKA STRATEGIC NOTES:
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
• Suzuka rewards aero balance & mechanical grip over raw speed
• 130R and S-Curves expose understeer/oversteer severely
• Hamilton's Suzuka_Confidence score (9.8) is the highest —
his tyre management (3.7 deg) could be decisive from P6
• Verstappen (P11) needs a Safety Car or chaos to recover —
Red Bull's "undriveable" setup is a massive concern here
• TyreDeg is MORE impactful at Suzuka than China — rear wear
through high-speed corners punishes aggressive setups
• McLaren's higher deg numbers (4.2–4.3) may hurt in longer stints
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
""")
